%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 1800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/2400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 2400w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1350px) 953px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 395px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 60px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 1800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/2400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg 2400w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1350px) 953px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 395px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 60px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3790x2369+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd9%2F68%2F71b003804b8c93b34801f165caf9%2Fgettyimages-2201579008.jpg" class="img" alt="A view of the ancient site of Gobekli Tepe, known as the world&amp;#039;s oldest temple, in Sanliurfa, Turkey, on Feb. 17." fetchpriority="high" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 A view of the ancient site of Gobekli Tepe, known as the world's oldest temple, in Sanliurfa, Turkey, on Feb. 17.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Mustafa Hatipoglu/Anadolu via Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;GOBEKLI TEPE, Turkey — Tour guide Sabahattin Alkan herds curious tourists through the scorching afternoon heat, luring them with the promise of something far stranger than your typical vacation snap.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"Over here on the right, you see a spaceship landed recently," he says with a grin.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;He's joking. Mostly. But more on that in a minute.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;We're in the Urfa plain, a dry, dusty stretch about 25 miles from the Turkish-Syrian border.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;That "spaceship" is actually just a curved roof. But what lies beneath the dome has sparked decades of mystery, curiosity — and conspiracy.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-81069" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 1600;         --source-height: 1200;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Faa%2F19%2F22dc07d94954b915ae90497526b5%2Fgobekli-tepe-11.jpeg" class="img" alt="One of the T-shaped pillars at Gobekli Tepe, depicting a bull, a fox and a crane. Scientists have spent decades trying to decode the story behind the symbols." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 One of the T-shaped pillars at Gobekli Tepe, depicting a bull, a fox and a crane. Scientists have spent decades trying to decode the story behind the symbols.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Rebecca Rosman for NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;"It's quite an interesting place, actually," Alkan assures his audience.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;He's talking about Gobekli Tepe, one of the oldest known archaeological sites on Earth, dating back nearly 12,000 years.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Alkan points to T-shaped limestone pillars carved with human arms, hands resting on stomachs, and wild animals: lions, foxes, boars, scorpions and birds among them.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Klaus Schmidt, the German archaeologist who led the site's first major excavations in the 1990s, called Gobekli Tepe "the world's oldest temple," theorizing that it brought together nomadic hunter-gatherers from across the Middle East.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-81065" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2835;         --source-height: 1883;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2835x1883+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2Fb9%2Fed2c94e849cd8410fabaca846f62%2Fgettyimages-1245984305.jpg" class="img" alt="German archaeologist Klaus Schmidt, who pioneered excavations at the ancient site of Gobekli Tepe, carries out research in Sanliurfa, Turkey, on May 18, 2008." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 German archaeologist Klaus Schmidt, who pioneered excavations at the ancient site of Gobekli Tepe, carries out research in Sanliurfa, Turkey, on May 18, 2008.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Mehmet Guldas/Anadolu Agency via Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Today, that view has shifted. Some now interpret it as a ceremonial gathering site, while others suggest it functioned as a social hub where rituals helped bind together early communities.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Emilie Salvesen, a tour operator visiting the site, says the question of whether there was a spiritual component to the site still fascinates her.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"Did they experience the divine in the way that we might think of it today?" she asks, gesturing toward one of the inscribed pillars. "I imagine it was much more existential."&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;The truth? Still mostly a mystery.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Scientists are regularly adjusting their hypotheses about the site's intended purpose. And it's not an easy investigation.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"Whatever we tell now, I don't know if it will be accurate information or not, because maybe our idea will change in another 50 years," Alkan says. "We're trying to predict 12,000 years ago."&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;But that uncertainty has thrown the door wide open for one specific group looking for answers: conspiracy theorists.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Conspiracy theories take root — with help from Joe Rogan&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Graham Hancock, a British journalist and star of the controversial Netflix series &lt;em&gt;Ancient Apocalypse&lt;/em&gt;, has &lt;a href="https://grahamhancock.com/hancockg23/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;theorized&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt; — without empirical evidence — that Gobekli Tepe was built by a "lost civilization" wiped out by an Ice Age cataclysm.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Once confined to the fringes, theories like Hancock's have gained mainstream traction — thanks in large part to Joe Rogan, whose massively popular podcast has become a platform for alternative takes on science and history.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;In November 2024, another Gobekli Tepe conspiracy theorist, Jimmy Corsetti, a YouTuber and self-described "ancient history investigator," &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YUavzFKgvjk" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;appeared&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt; on Rogan's podcast, bringing with him a slew of speculations and wild theories about the site.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Among them, Corsetti accused archaeologists of intentionally dragging their feet and hiding key discoveries about the site.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"We're talking about pillars buried in dirt. It's 2024. Don't tell me we don't have the technology!" Corsetti told Rogan.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-81071" class="bucketwrap image x-large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4500;         --source-height: 2994;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 1800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/2400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 2400w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1350px) 953px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 395px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 60px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 1800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/2400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg 2400w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1350px) 953px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 395px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 60px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F76%2F00%2F8aed704c4170aef0217228c4c8de%2Fgettyimages-1241209826.jpg" class="img" alt="An aerial view shows archaeologists and workers at Gobekli Tepe on May 18, 2022." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 An aerial view shows archaeologists and workers at Gobekli Tepe on May 18, 2022.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Ozan Kose/AFP via Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Corsetti accused archaeologists of moving slowly on purpose, perhaps to preserve the mystery and keep the curious tourists coming.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Only a small percentage of the site has been dug up since excavations began in the mid-1990s. And with Rogan's platform behind them, theorists like Corsetti have helped turn that slow progress into a source of global suspicion.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;A scientist responds&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Lee Clare, an archaeologist who has led the excavation site for over a decade, has heard it all — including the outlandish theories.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Speaking from his office in Istanbul, with the Bosporus glinting behind him, Clare shrugs off the conspiracists.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-81067" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 1600;         --source-height: 1200;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/1600x1200+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7e%2Fe0%2Ff886d50d4b4fadf4315ec5bee83e%2Flee-clare-2.jpeg" class="img" alt="Archaeologist Lee Clare, photographed at his office in Istanbul, has overseen the Gobekli Tepe archaeological site for over a decade." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Archaeologist Lee Clare, photographed at his office in Istanbul, has overseen the Gobekli Tepe archaeological site for over a decade.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Rebecca Rosman for NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;"Some of these guys go to the site for half an hour and think they can explain the whole site," he says of the budding conspiracy theorists.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;When it comes to Gobekli Tepe, Clare says archaeologists aren't hiding anything. They're trying to protect it.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;"You can't just bulldoze a site to get everything out. That's the wrong approach," he says.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;In other words, archaeology moves slowly for a reason. Every layer tells part of the story. And once you dig through each layer, it's gone for good, as are its secrets.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"Why would I be so selfish as to dig the entire site … and take these possibilities away from future generations of archaeologists?"&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Clare says he grew up playing with toy dinosaurs and always wanted to be an archaeologist. He never expected to end up the target of conspiracy theories. But here we are.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"It goes onto the personal level as well," he says, which is why he deleted his social media accounts.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"I want to stay sane in this situation."&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;12,000 years of storytelling&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;The real danger here isn't just misinformation, according to Clare. It's that these competing narratives risk drowning out the real story, the one scientists have spent decades trying to properly decode.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"There are a lot of narratives out there about Gobekli Tepe. The question is, whose narrative is correct? And I think we'll never know."&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;One of the few things scientists do know for sure?&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Gobekli Tepe is proof that humans have been storytellers dating back at least 12,000 years.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-81070" class="bucketwrap image x-large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4500;         --source-height: 2994;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 1800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/2400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 2400w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1350px) 953px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 395px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 60px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 1800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/2400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg 2400w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1350px) 953px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 395px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 60px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4500x2994+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0a%2Fc8%2F6a165a0f444abf15223f0db9f86b%2Fgettyimages-1241210304.jpg" class="img" alt="Visitors look at pillars at the archaeological site of Gobekli Tepe in Sanliurfa, Turkey, on May 18, 2022." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Visitors look at pillars at the archaeological site of Gobekli Tepe in Sanliurfa, Turkey, on May 18, 2022.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Ozan Kose/AFP via Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The carvings on the T-shaped pillars — the lions, foxes and hands — they're all stories.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;We just don't know what they say. Gobekli Tepe may be the first place humans come together to share meaning.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;And like all good stories, this one's still open to interpretation.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
